<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1235,1478]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,418,1235,1261]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Revised diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[766,975,1235,1261]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[766,975,1235,1261]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">M. appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the medial processes of the tenth abdominal tergite: the inner margins and apices touching each other. The female differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[1229,1436,1271,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[1229,1436,1271,1297]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">M. appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the projections at the anterior margin of subgenital plate smaller, more flattened (in lateral view), and shorter in length than subgenital plate. Other minor differences include the male subgenital plate more transverse, ca. 2.5 times wider than long; the ovipositor &lt;
<quantity box="[519,619,1379,1406]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" unit="mm" value="16.5">16.5 mm</quantity>
in length, shorter than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[879,1087,1379,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[879,1087,1379,1405]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">M. appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
